{"version": "https://jsonfeed.org/version/1", "title": "Xiaochuan's blog", "home_page_url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/", "feed_url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/feed_json_updated.json", "description": "life is short", "icon": null, "authors": [], "language": "en", "items": [{"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2024/12/18/mkdocs-intro/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2024/12/18/mkdocs-intro/", "title": "Technical writing with material for mkdocs", "content_html": "<h1>Technical writing with material for mkdocs</h1>\n<p>!!! abstract\n    <a href=\"https://squidfunk.github.io/mkdocs-material/\">Material for mkdocs</a> is a documentation framework adopted by\n    many popular python libraries e.g. <a href=\"https://docs.pola.rs/\">this</a>, <a href=\"https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/\">this</a> and\n    <a href=\"https://docs.astral.sh/uv/\">this</a>.\n    The plugins and markdown extensions make writing rich technical content delightful e.g. maths, code,\n    docstring parsers, and more. The main apeal of the project is that \"it's just markdown\"\n    (with a bit of extended syntax). This tutorial provides a step by step intro to setting up a blog website\n    (such as this one!) with this framework.</p>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-05-31T20:57:37+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["Tutorial", "dev tools"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/02/15/survive/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/02/15/survive/", "title": "The Cox survival guide: hazards, models and time", "content_html": "<h1>The Cox survival guide: hazards, models and time</h1>\n<p>!!! abstract\n    This note is an overview of survival analysis with a focus on the Cox proportional hazards model, a key tool for modelling time-to-event data. We define hazard functions, address right-censoring, and derive estimators like Nelson-Aalen and Kaplan-Meier. The Cox model's semiparametric form and partial likelihood estimation are discussed, along with evaluation metrics such as concordance probability.</p>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-05-31T20:57:37+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["Note", "industrial mathematics"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/04/05/fork-merge-and-pr/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/04/05/fork-merge-and-pr/", "title": "Fork, merge and PR", "content_html": "<h1>Fork, merge and PR</h1>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-05-31T20:57:37+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["Tutorial", "dev tools"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/04/20/df-gen-polars/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/04/20/df-gen-polars/", "title": "Generate test dataframe with polars (powered by hypothesis)", "content_html": "<h1>Generate test dataframe with <code>polars</code> (powered by <code>hypothesis</code>)</h1>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-05-31T20:57:37+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["TIL", "data engineering"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/04/24/llm-eval-for-my-personal-usage/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/04/24/llm-eval-for-my-personal-usage/", "title": "LLM eval for my personal usage", "content_html": "<h1>LLM eval for my personal usage</h1>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-05-31T20:57:37+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["LLM", "TIL"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/04/25/an-interesting-case-study-of-polars-in-production/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/04/25/an-interesting-case-study-of-polars-in-production/", "title": "An interesting case study of polars in production", "content_html": "<h1>An interesting case study of polars in production</h1>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-05-31T20:57:37+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["TIL", "data engineering"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/05/21/repurposing-github-for-mathematical-research/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/05/21/repurposing-github-for-mathematical-research/", "title": "Repurposing GitHub for Mathematical Research", "content_html": "<h1>Repurposing GitHub for Mathematical Research</h1>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-05-31T20:57:37+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["TIL", "research"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/05/25/gpu-puzzles-annotated/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/05/25/gpu-puzzles-annotated/", "title": "GPU puzzles annotated", "content_html": "<h1>GPU puzzles annotated</h1>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-05-31T20:57:37+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["TIL", "low latency"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/05/26/working-with-large-datasets-in-snowflake/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/05/26/working-with-large-datasets-in-snowflake/", "title": "Working with Large Datasets in Snowflake", "content_html": "<h1>Working with Large Datasets in Snowflake</h1>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-05-31T20:57:37+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["TIL", "data engineering"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/05/01/static-site-generator-using-fasthtml/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/05/01/static-site-generator-using-fasthtml/", "title": "Static site generator using fasthtml", "content_html": "<h1>Static site generator using fasthtml</h1>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-05-31T20:57:37+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["TIL", "dev tools"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/05/19/intro-to-snowpark-api/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/05/19/intro-to-snowpark-api/", "title": "Intro to Snowpark API", "content_html": "<h1>Intro to Snowpark API</h1>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-05-31T00:00:00+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["TIL", "data engineering"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/05/14/data-quality/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/05/14/data-quality/", "title": "A Dimensional Approach to Data Quality Principles", "content_html": "<h1>A Dimensional Approach to Data Quality Principles</h1>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-05-18T00:00:00+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["TIL", "data engineering"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/04/06/polars-streaming-tricks/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/04/06/polars-streaming-tricks/", "title": "Polars streaming tricks", "content_html": "<h1>Polars streaming tricks</h1>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-05-01T00:00:00+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["TIL", "data engineering"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/04/13/mortgate/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/04/13/mortgate/", "title": "Build a mortgate calculator with fasthtml", "content_html": "<h1>Build a mortgate calculator with fasthtml</h1>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-04-15T00:00:00+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["Tutorial", "dev tools"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2024/12/21/essentials-of-polars-for-pandas-experts/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2024/12/21/essentials-of-polars-for-pandas-experts/", "title": "Essentials of polars for pandas experts", "content_html": "<h1>Essentials of <code>polars</code> for <code>pandas</code> experts</h1>\n<p>!!! abstract\n    <code>pandas</code> is a standard tool for every data professional, although it does not scale well in production.\n    Yet, being a standard is a strategic position to be, as libraries coming to solve the scale issue tend to meet data professionals where they are, by mimicing the <code>pandas</code> API (think: <code>dask</code>, <code>pyspark.pandas</code>).</p>\n<pre><code>`polars` is a new-ish tool that is probably replacing `pandas` at the time of writing. The goal of this post is to introduce the kind of mindset change needed to fully exploit `polars` in production.\n</code></pre>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-04-07T00:00:00+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["Tutorial", "data engineering"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/01/12/intro-to-jax/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/01/12/intro-to-jax/", "title": "Intro to Jax", "content_html": "<h1>Intro to Jax</h1>\n<p>!!! abstract\n    Mutiple packages came to solve the speed issue of <code>python</code> in scientific computing. The de facto standard is of course <code>numpy</code>. Think also <code>numba</code>, <code>jax</code>, <code>torch</code> or even a new language :fire: that go beyond what <code>numpy</code> offers.  This post is a quick intro to my personal preference as of Jan 2025. </p>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-01-31T00:00:00+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["Tutorial", "low latency"]}, {"id": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/01/03/mini-tutorial-for-python-packaging-release-and-publish/", "url": "https://xiaochuany.github.io/blog/2025/01/03/mini-tutorial-for-python-packaging-release-and-publish/", "title": "Mini-tutorial for python packaging, release and publish", "content_html": "<h1>Mini-tutorial for python packaging, release and publish</h1>\n<p>!!! abstract \n    This mini-tutorial is a beginner's cheatsheet to python packaging. Check <a href=\"https://packaging.python.org/en/latest/\">Python packaing user guide</a> for an authoritative guidance on the topic.  </p>", "image": null, "date_modified": "2025-01-10T00:00:00+00:00", "authors": [{"name": "Xiaochuan Yang"}], "tags": ["Tutorial", "dev tools"]}]}